2026-04-16 12:36:36 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Output Cable (+) fast-connection terminal'] hypothesis_explanation="There is a direct, low-resistance (0.01 Ω) continuity between the relay output terminal and the Control Output Cable (+), yet the voltage drops from 11.98 V at the relay output to 0.36 V at the Cable (+) terminal. This is not consistent with normal copper wiring, even with minor resistance, as there shouldn't be such a dramatic voltage drop with essentially no load. The likely culprit is a faulty or internally corroded/oxidized fast-connection terminal (at the Control Output Cable +), which can pass continuity and test as a short, but under any real current load it exhibits a very high contact resistance that causes the drastic voltage drop. This is a classic failure mode for push-fit or fast-connection terminals, especially if there is invisible corrosion or internal mechanical failure inside the housing."
